The '''1978 Arab League summit''' was meeting held between Arab leaders on 2 November in [[Baghdad]] as the 9th [[Arab League Summit]]. The summit came in the aftermath of the [[Egypt]]'s [[Anwar Sadat]]'s unilateral [[Camp David Accords|peace treaty]] with [[Israel]]. The conference resolved that the agreements signed by the Egyptian Government at Camp David harmed the rights of the Palestinian people. The Egyptian government was urged not to ratify the agreements and to align itself with the Arab League. Most importantly, the League froze its relations with the Government of Egypt.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.washingtoninstitute.org/policy-analysis/view/arab-league-summit-conferences-19642000|title=Arab League Summit Conferences, 1964–2000|website=www.washingtoninstitute.org|access-date=9 May 2016}}</ref> On 31 March 1979, five days after the ratification of the [[Egypt-Israel Peace Treaty]],<ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YAd8efHdVzIC|title=The Encyclopedia of the Arab-Israeli Conflict: A Political, Social, and Military History [4 volumes]: A Political, Social, and Military History|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C.|last2=Roberts|first2=Priscilla|date=12 May 2008|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781851098422|language=en}}</ref> Arab leaders again convened in Baghdad in the absence of Egypt and decided to expel it from the Arab League.<ref name=":1" /> Consequently, the secretariat of the League was moved out of its [[Cairo]] headquarters to [[Tunis]].<ref name=":1" /> This decision was slowly reversed in the 1980s after president [[Hosni Mubarak]] ascended to power.  Egypt, which regained strong influence in the region as rival nation Syria was suffering setbacks during the [[Lebanon Civil War]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q0J0nJktlWIC|title=Syria and the Middle East Peace Process|last=Drysdale|first=Alasdair|last2=Hinnebusch|first2=Raymond A.|date=1 January 1991|publisher=Council on Foreign Relations|isbn=9780876091050|language=en}}</ref> returned to the Arab League on 23 May 1989<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2245&dat=19890523&id=gZkzAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dTIHAAAAIBAJ&pg=2785,3248878|title=Lodi News-Sentinel - Google News Archive Search|website=news.google.com|access-date=9 May 2016}}</ref> and the headquarters, which never saw completed construction in Tunis,<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1990/03/12/world/arab-league-headquarters-to-return-to-cairo.html|title=Arab League Headquarters to Return to Cairo|last=Times|first=Alan Cowell, Special To The New York|date=12 March 1990|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=9 May 2016}}</ref> return to Cairo on 12 March 1990.<ref name=":0" />

