{{Infobox summit | summit_name = Bonn summit | image = NATO expansion.png | caption = Map of NATO members | country = [[West Germany]] | dates = June 10, 1982 }} The '''1982 Bonn summit''' was the 6th [[NATO summit]] bringing the leaders of member nations together at the same time. The formal sessions and informal meetings in [[Bonn]] took place on June 10, 1982.<ref name="nato1">{{cite web|title=NATO summit meetings |author=NATO |url=http://www.nato.int/issues/summits/index.html#agendas |work= |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5gWo4KcXm?url=http://www.nato.int/issues/summits/index.html |archivedate=2009-05-04 |deadurl=yes |accessdate=2009-03-18 |df= }}</ref> This event was only the fifth meeting of the NATO heads of state following the ceremonial signing of the [[North Atlantic Treaty]] on April 4, 1949.<ref name="thomas101">Thomas, Ian Q.R. (1997). [https://books.google.com/books?id=mwYQSw00m8EC&pg=PA223&dq=NATO+and+Brussels+summit+1974#PPA101,M1 ''The promise of alliance: NATO and the political imagination,'' p. 101.]</ref> When the summit was held, there were sixteen members of [[NATO]].
==Background== In this period, the organization faced unresolved questions concerned whether a new generation of leaders would be as committed to NATO as their predecessors had been.<ref name="thomas101"/> The Bonn Summit addressed many issues and discussed many topics. Most notable of these topics was the accession of [[Spain]] to [[NATO]], as the summit was held years after the fall of [[Francisco Franco]].<ref>[http://www.nato.int/docu/comm/49-95/c820610a.htm]</ref> The summit also voiced concern to the perceived threat the [[Soviet Union]] posed to members of NATO.
